\section{Summary}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Summary}

 

\begin{itemize}
 
 \item Paper 1:


 \begin{itemize}
  \item The energy dispersions of the three uppermost VBs are strongly anisotropic and non-parabolic even very close to the $\Gamma$-point VBM.
\item The full band parameterization is valid around 0.5 eV below VBM and 0.5 eV above the conduction band minimum (CBM).
\item All the three CuIn\textsubscript{1-x}Ga\textsubscript{x}Se\textsubscript{2} ($x$ = 0, 0.5, and 1.0) compositions show comparable \textbf{k}-dependency of their effective hole masses.
\end{itemize}

 \item Paper 2:
 
 \begin{itemize}
\item An energy-dependent DOS mass is introduced, and it can be utilized to describe
the carrier concentration and the Fermi energy using traditional equations for the DOS.
\item The transition from the freeze-out region to the extrinsic region occurs well below the room temperature for uncompensated acceptor concentration below 
around 10\textsuperscript{17} cm\textsuperscript{$-$3}, whereas for higher concentrations, not all acceptors are ionized at \textit{T} = 300 K. Thus, a more correct description of the energy dispersions is needed.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
 \begin{itemize}
\item Paper 3:

 \begin{itemize}
\item  The dielectric function calculated by our theoretical method shows a good agreement with the result of experiment.
\item  Electronic origins of the observed critical-point (CP) features are discussed based on our theoretical calculations.
\item  The pairs of valence and conduction bands along the main symmetry directions of Brillouin zone are suggested for the major CP features based on our theoretical calculations.
\end{itemize}

\end{itemize}



\end{frame}

